As Jay wrote to Dr. Math
On 08/15/2004 at 20:05:53 (Eastern Time),
>[Question]
>How can I solve an inequality with terms that don't factor (easily), 
>such as:
>
>x^3 - x^2 - x + 1 > 0
>
>[Difficulty]
>If all the terms shared a common factor, like an "x", this wouldn't 
>be a problem - just factor, reverse "FOIL". But the 1 at the end is 
>the obstacle. Even if you disregard the 1 and factor an x from the 
>rest of the terms on the left side,(x^2 - x - 1) doesn't factor 
>without the quadratic equation. Am i missing something?
>
>[Thoughts]
>first, i tried to change 1 into (x/x) so i could factor out an x so 
>that the left side was (x)(x^2 -x -1 + 1/x) but i got stuck. next, i 
>tried to move the 1 to the right side, making the inequality 
>x^3...>-1, but this is wrong because to factor you need a zero on the 
>right side. here, i am stuck.

Hi Jay,

Thanks for writing to Dr Math.  Did you notice that

  x - 1

is a factor of the left side of the equation?

If you have any questions about this or need more help, please write
back and show me what you have been able to do, and I will try to
offer further suggestions.

